TY  - JOUR
T1  - Product Innovation and Start-Up Business Market Share Performance
AU  - Robinson, William T.
Y1  - 1990/10/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.36.10.1279
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.36.10.1279
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1279
EP  - 1289
VL  - 36
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This empirical study estimates the impact of several product innovation attributes on initial market share. We find that the product's advantage relative to competing products has the strongest market share impact. Incompatibility with customers' existing way of doing things does not have a meaningful market share impact. By reducing market share, a new and proprietary product technology tends to act as a barrier to adoption, unless the effect is offset by a major product advantage.
AB  - This empirical study estimates the impact of several product innovation attributes on initial market share. We find that the product's advantage relative to competing products has the strongest market share impact. Incompatibility with customers' existing way of doing things does not have a meaningful market share impact. By reducing market share, a new and proprietary product technology tends to act as a barrier to adoption, unless the effect is offset by a major product advantage.
